title: For Sale:  Winchester M1 Garand Rifle, Very Rare.!
postcontent: The Gas Plug is a single slot type which is period correct and is most likely a replacement as the blued finish is almost 100%.The barrel was made by Springfield but has a Winchester proof visible when the op rod is locked back. There are no Springfield proof marks meaning that Springfield never assembled it and only the drawing number, date and steel batch code are SA. This surprised us and after a few phone calls to elderly collectors and authorities on the Garand we were assured that although unusual and very rare this is a product of sharing or loaning of parts to keep production output unbroken by delays. Parts sharing or use of other manufacturers parts was more common place than most people think but was very poorly documented and it is likely that only a few hundred at the most may have been built this way and even fewer would have survived post war rebuilds. The bore has strong lands and grooves and has been through the rebuild process as there is hard chrome around the gas port .

title: For Sale:  Springfield Trapdoor Sporting Rifle (AL4061)
postcontent: Springfield Trapdoor Sporting Rifle .40-65 caliber. Low serial #19xxx on breech. During 1883 Hartley and Graham bought surplus Trapdoor rifles from the U.S. Government and had them converted (possibly by Whitney) into beautiful sporting rifles to satisfy demand from the Western Buffalo Trade. A new heavy barrel, blued and octagonal (approximately #4 size and weight). Barrel length 30” and mounted with a Buckhorn/Ladder rear sight and Rocky Mountain German silver front sight. The original U.S. stock was reworked producing a Schnable forend with a black buffalo horn insert. The stock was checkered. Butt plate has the compartment for cleaning rods. Note: There is a faint U.S. Inspectors cartouche remaining on the stock. These guns were retailed by E.C. Meacham of St. Louis, N. Curry & Bro. San Francisco, John P. Lovell of Boston. This was the perfect big bore, big barrel rifle for Western big game. True fact: more buffalo were killed with Trapdoors than any other rifle! This beautiful rifle has 95-96% original barrel blue. Receiver has 98% bright original case colors as does the lock. Checkering is excellent. Great example of a buffalo hunter’s heavy barrel rifle and in great condition.Any questions? title: For Sale:  RUGER ~ RARE VAQUERO .40S&W STAINLESS 4-5/8...Mfd in 2000...LIKE NEW IN BOX
postcontent: Here's a very scarce revolver for the Ruger collector. This is an original Vaquero single-action revolver that is chambered for the .40 S&W cartridge. The story behind these is rather interesting and can be read about here: Vaquero .40 S&W San Diego Sheriff Commemorative. In a nutshell, just over 1000 of these revolvers were special ordered from Ruger to be used to make up a special engraved police commemorative revolver. A relative handful (fewer than 200) were never engraved and these are now highly sought after by collectors. This is one of those scarce Vaqueros, Ruger catalog number KBNV-404SW. It is constructed of polished stainless steel and wears the short 4-5/8" barrel with fixed sights. Condition is excellent and although the gun has been fired, it has not seen much use. The stainless finish shows only a few very light handling marks that could easily be polished out if desired. There is no rust or pitting. I'd grade this revolver at 98% overall. The original wood grips are excellent also, free of cracks, chips, or dings. The mechanics are in perfect working order and the bore is excellent. This hard-to-find Ruger comes in the original plastic case which numbers to the gun. The owner's manual, miscellaneous paperwork, and small safety lock are included. Manufactured back in 2000, this is a unique variation of the original Vaquero.Buyer pays $20.00 shipping.
